I goofed one late night and tried to push a large file from my local repository to github.  The file was properly rejected, but the github history maintained the location of the now-removed file.  Despite several rounds of cleaning the local repository (by bfg and filter branch), I was never able to push the cleaned repo and history back to github.  Eventually I gave up and just created a new github repo and pushed to that, but unfortunately I lost the record of the students' commits.

I followed the help directions carefully, read a good part of the github pro book, and talked with several people.  Despite this, I couldn't solve the problem in a more elegant way.  So I suggest you have a section on trouble-shooting.

answer-59:
I can only use it for open source. I'd like to use it for my business's code too, but your billing model excludes that. I'm currently bootstrapping a startup.

I have a lot of closed source repos that I need to backup somewhere, and all things being equal, GitHub would be my first choice.

All things are not equal.

I've got 3 closed source repos that I'm actively using at the moment, but altogether I've got 39. I collaborate with just 2 other people, and that's only on two of those private repos.

I store them all on Bitbucket. Why? Because at the scale I'm currently at, it's free.

I'm really just using Bitbucket for backup. None of my private repos are making any money yet, so the $50/month cost of hosting all that stuff on GitHub is actually fairly significant. I'd be paying for it out of my own pocket.

Bitbucket's billing model (up to five collaborators are free) seems to fit much better with the way small companies grow. I can't afford to pay for code hosting until my startup is making money. Once it's making money I'm likely to need to start hiring. I'll be paying those people, at which point the $50/month for GitHub will seem like a drop in the ocean, and I'd happily pay that for the collaboration features.

Only I won't, because I'm now entrenched in Bitbucket. If you check my user ID (@gma) you'll find I've been on GitHub since the early days. And yet I use Bitbucket, and they're going to make money out of me once I start hiring and cross their collaboration threshold. Something must be wrong with that, mustn't it?

I once explained this to Scott C in a pub, but he said that they'd run the numbers and that people like me weren't in GitHub's target market.

answer-45:
The issue tracker needs some attention, or a redesign, or integration with a service dedicated to issue tracking. It isn't usable for medium or larger projects. Things like (saveable) custom reports like trac has, or submitter-initiated labeling of new issues, among others, are basically must-haves, otherwise issue trackers become piles of backlog unless people spend countless hours triaging.

Unrelatedly, it'd be nice if GitHub started showing off a bit more of how it's a nice *interface* on top of things that generally git can do already. E.g., find a way to indicate to users how the blame tab corresponds to `git blame`, how clicking the green button relates to `git merge`, etc. etc. In particular besides being useful for learning, not having that means that people who know how git works (ha ha) probably find it hard to use parts of GitHub because it isn't obvious what *exactly* they're doing to the repo (e.g., "does the green button do a ff merge? No? Yes? Going to have to click to find out.")

Other small annoyances, like not being able to turn off pull requests on a repo (is that still true?)
answer-59: Well, probably "open source a bit more of it so that I could fix my own annoyances." I guess that's a bit like wishing for more wishes.

capture more of the build/release story. Allow people using build tools like Maven (or npm, or...) to deploy to a staged repository using a repo manager that makes sense for that technology, and support accessing those artifacts in the context of released ones (grouping released stuff with the staged stuff logicall for testing)...then, provide them with a way to promote those staged releases and have it picked up into global repository instances (maven central, the global npm registry, etc).

Right now, I have to work with GitHub for the source side of things, and Sonatype for the release side of things. I'd like to have it all in one place...and IMO most languages are moving toward this repo-centric development model, so it makes sense to have analogous infrastructure for other langs.

You guys do a great job with the source side, and you're making inroads into the project-management side of things (sort of pre-source, in a way). I'd like to see you expand into the post-source side too.

If it were an open source platform.

answer-45:
The Wiki is really, really bad.  Even by Wikipedia/MediaWiki standards it's bad.

The issue tracker is promising and has some great integration with commits, but is still rather basic as such systems go.  Even the features that are there require too much hand-holding.  It should be easier to draw from a common pool of tags; the idea that every project must create its own tag list is annoying.

In a system which is all about versioning, editing an issue should create a history...modeled like StackOverflow's versioning on posts.  They've got that down pretty well, including the 5 minute grace period to not create a new version if you were just editing out typos or having a quick second thought.
answer-59:
One wish that is the wish for unlimited wish fulfillment: Release your platform as free software under the Affero General Public License!

There's already open source alternatives to GitHub, that are...not as good.  There are closed source alternatives to GitHub that are...eh, about as good.  (Better at some things, not as good at others, almost always less ergonomic.)

GitHub.com would be the central place where GitHub features are worked on.  You are the ones who know how to deploy and work on it.  Maybe a clone site would pop up here or there; but the odds of them rising as trustworthy competitors for a commercial audience would be slim.  If they made any unique features they would be required to release the code under the Affero terms.

GitHub already has good PR with open source, this would seal the deal pretty much forever by being the first to make the announcement.  Go from being admired for being fairly good to being gods.  Continue collecting revenue as the #1 host for commercial projects using the open source platform and let an army of little patching ants ensure your platform is the only one people consider using.

answer-59:
Significantly better branch management. I'd like to know what branch was branched from what. I'd also like to set some default branches that pull requests will go into.

For example, now that our product is mature, we very rarely merge pull requests into master. Thus, it would nice if, when making a pull request, it would be smart enough to know that a lot of pull requests targeted the "November Release" branch, and thus had "November Release" in some form of an auto-complete.

Likewise, I'd also like to know that "November Release" was branched from master, but "December Release" was branched from "November Release." This might change, because once "November Release" is merged into master, "December Release" changes to be branched from master.

Likewise, we probably have about 500 "dead" branches in our repository, because these have already been merged to master. I'd like to be able to clean up these dead branches quickly, to reduce clutter.
